  <text xml:lang="ta" type="edition">
    <body>
      <div xml:id="NA34-kiḷavi">
        <p type="edition">itu tōḻi teyvattukku uraippāḷāy veṟi vilakkiyatu.</p>
        <p type="translation" xml:lang="en">This is how the confidante prevents the Veṟi dance as one speaking to the deity.</p>
      </div>
      <div xml:id="NA34">
        <lg type="edition">
<l>            kaṭavuṭ kaṟcuṉai yaṭaiyiṟan taviḻnta</l>
<l>            paṟiyāk kuvaḷai malaroṭu kāntaṭ</l>
<l>            kuruti yoṇpū vurukeḻak kaṭṭip</l>
<l>            peruvarai yaṭukkam poṟpac cūrmaka</l>
<l>            ḷaruvi yiṉṉiyat tāṭu nāṭaṉ </l>
<l>            mārputara vanta paṭarmali yarunōy</l>
<l>            niṉṉaṇaṅ kaṉmai yaṟintu maṇṇāntu</l>
<l>            kārnaṟuṅ kaṭampiṉ kaṇṇi cūṭi</l>
<l>            vēlaṉ vēṇṭa veṟimaṉai vantōy</l>
<l>            kaṭavu ḷāyiṉu māka </l>
<l>            maṭavai maṉṟa vāḻiya murukē.</l>
            </lg>
        <lg type="translation" xml:lang="en">
<l>Foolish indeed [are] you, may you live, Murukaṉ,</l>
<l rend="indent2">since you have come, even though a god, to the house</l>
<l rend="indent">for the Veṟi dance when the spear-bearing [priest] requires [it],</l>
<l rend="indent">wearing a chaplet from the Kaṭampa smelling of the rainy season,</l>
<l rend="indent">head held erect, although you know of it not being your torment</l>
<l rend="indent">[that is] the difficult pain abounding in affliction that came as given</l>
<l rend="indent2">by the chest of the man from a land,</l>
<l rend="indent">where the fearful damsels are dancing beautifully(?) to the sweet</l>
<l rend="indent">sound of the waterfall on the side of the big mountain, tying,</l>
<l rend="indent">having tied in a shapely way bright blood flowers</l>
<l rend="indent2">of Malabar lily together with blossoms of white waterlilies, unplucked,</l>
<l rend="indent2">traversing the leaves<note place="foot">Here the variant <term xml:lang="ta">iṭai-y-iṟantu</term> is to be considered. It is conceivable that the blossoms are big enough to pass over the leaves, but it is at least equally well to think of abundance: growing all over the place.</note> [and] opening in the god’s stony mountain pools.</l>
        </lg>
         </div>
